      <description>&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;div id=&#34;probability-functions&#34; class=&#34; solved&#34;&gt;&lt;h5 class=&#34;solved&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;div class=&#34;d-inline-flex flex-row m-0 p-0 &#34;&gt;Probability functions&#xA;      &#xA;      &amp;nbsp;&#xA;      &lt;button &#xA;        class=&#34;btn p-0 m-0 border-0&#34; &#xA;        aria-expanded=&#34;false&#34;&#xA;        aria-controls=&#34;probability-functionsSolution&#34;&#xA;        onclick=&#34;showPasswordModal(&#39;probability-functionsSolution&#39;, &#39;exc-prob&#39;)&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;i class=&#34;bi bi-lightbulb-fill&#34;&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/button&gt;&#xA;      &#xA;      &#xA;    &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h5&gt;&lt;p&gt;Suppose we&amp;rsquo;re dealing with a coin-flip, which we analyze in a propositional&#xA;language with $\neg,\land,\lor$ and propositional variables:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;$$\mathsf{HEADS}\mid \mathsf{TAILS}.$$&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Our aim is to define a probability for each formula $A\in\mathcal{L}$.&#xA;We&amp;rsquo;re wondering whether a given set of conditions is sufficient for this&#xA;purpose.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Since the general question whether a given condition defines a total probability&#xA;function is a bit too complicated at this point, we&amp;rsquo;ll work with the following&#xA;four formulas as our test cases:&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Logical learning</title>
      <link>https://logicalmethods.ai/exercises/learning/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://logicalmethods.ai/exercises/learning/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;For the last workgroup, we just have one exercise that illustrate an important&#xA;concepts about Bayesian learning. The rest of the workgroup you can use to ask&#xA;questions for the exam.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;div id=&#34;base-rate-fallacy&#34; class=&#34; solved&#34;&gt;&lt;h5 class=&#34;solved&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;div class=&#34;d-inline-flex flex-row m-0 p-0 &#34;&gt;Base-rate fallacy&#xA;      &#xA;      &amp;nbsp;&#xA;      &lt;button &#xA;        class=&#34;btn p-0 m-0 border-0&#34; &#xA;        aria-expanded=&#34;false&#34;&#xA;        aria-controls=&#34;base-rate-fallacySolution&#34;&#xA;        onclick=&#34;showPasswordModal(&#39;base-rate-fallacySolution&#39;, &#39;exc-learn&#39;)&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;i class=&#34;bi bi-lightbulb-fill&#34;&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/button&gt;&#xA;      &#xA;      &#xA;    &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h5&gt;&lt;p&gt;The &lt;i class=&#34;bi bi-box-arrow-up-right h-6&#34;&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Base_rate_fallacy&#34; class=&#34;link-dark&#34; rel=&#34;external&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;base-rate fallacy&lt;/a&gt;&#xA; is&#xA;about a common misestimation concerning conditional probabilities.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;A simple example concerns diagnostic tests for rare diseases.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Suppose that a certain disease has a prevalence of 1% in the population. This is&#xA;already quite high, most &amp;ldquo;serious&amp;rdquo; infectious diseases have a way lower&#xA;prevalence in the general population.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
